WEBVTT

00:12.358 --> 00:14.061
‐ Another three bodies
were found by the Hackensack Mall
last night.

00:14.095 --> 00:16.432
That brings the total
body count to 11.

00:16.466 --> 00:19.205
Police are still searching
for the mass murderer.

00:19.238 --> 00:21.510
‐ ♪ Oh, the days
in Hickory Meadows ♪

00:21.544 --> 00:25.518
♪ A beautiful place to live,
not die ♪

00:25.552 --> 00:29.125
♪ Oh, the day
in Hickory Meadows ♪

00:29.158 --> 00:30.662
♪ Why ♪

00:30.695 --> 00:33.668
‐ [breathing heavily]

00:33.701 --> 00:36.507
[gasps]

00:36.540 --> 00:39.445
[menacing music]

00:39.478 --> 00:46.459
♪ ♪

00:47.729 --> 00:49.198
‐ [gasps]

00:50.133 --> 00:53.073
[Billie Eilish's "Copycat"]

00:53.106 --> 00:57.649
♪ ♪

00:57.682 --> 00:59.853
‐ ♪ Don't be cautious ♪

00:59.886 --> 01:01.624
♪ Don't be kind ♪

01:01.657 --> 01:05.732
♪ You committed,
I'm your crime ♪

01:05.765 --> 01:08.504
♪ Push my button anytime ♪

01:08.537 --> 01:10.541
♪ You got your finger
on the trigger ♪

01:10.575 --> 01:13.213
♪ But your
trigger finger's mine ♪

01:13.246 --> 01:15.284
♪ Silver dollar ♪

01:15.317 --> 01:17.154
♪ Golden flame ♪

01:17.187 --> 01:18.691
♪ Dirty water ♪

01:18.724 --> 01:20.695
♪ Poison rain ♪

01:20.728 --> 01:22.732
♪ Perfect murder ♪

01:22.766 --> 01:25.838
♪ Take your aim,
I don't belong to anyone ♪

01:25.872 --> 01:28.577
♪ But everybody
knows my name ♪

01:28.611 --> 01:34.455
♪ ♪

01:34.488 --> 01:35.758
‐ Hi, Jake.

01:35.792 --> 01:37.762
20 bucks for that.
Sound fair?

01:37.796 --> 01:39.298
‐ 20 bucks?

01:39.332 --> 01:42.171
‐ It's got to be worth
20 bucks, right?

01:42.204 --> 01:44.342
‐ Hey, where'd you get this?
‐ I have no idea.

01:44.375 --> 01:46.379
Must've been my daughter's,
I guess.

01:46.412 --> 01:48.751
Honestly, I don't remember.
You into vintage?

01:48.784 --> 01:50.588
‐ No, I'm into retro.

01:50.622 --> 01:52.291
‐ Oh, what's the difference?

01:52.324 --> 01:54.696
‐ About 10 bucks.
‐ [chuckles] Fair enough.

01:54.730 --> 01:57.669
♪ ♪

01:57.702 --> 02:00.875
‐ Well, thanks, Mrs. Jolly.
‐ Tell your dad I said hello.

02:02.812 --> 02:04.783
Oh.

02:04.816 --> 02:06.787
Someone took the butcher knife.

02:06.820 --> 02:08.758
‐ ♪ Call me calloused ♪

02:08.791 --> 02:10.795
♪ Call me cold ♪

02:10.828 --> 02:14.603
♪ You're italic, I'm in bold ♪

02:14.636 --> 02:17.609
♪ Call me cocky,
watch your tone ♪

02:17.642 --> 02:22.786
♪ You better love me
'cause you're just a clone ♪

02:22.819 --> 02:26.560
‐ What's up, detectives?
It's me, Devon Evans.

02:26.593 --> 02:29.332
Here in Hackensack,
the mayor likes to say

02:29.365 --> 02:31.570
the saints are always
watching over us,

02:31.603 --> 02:35.177
guiding our destinies
and keeping us from harm.

02:35.210 --> 02:37.314
Well, I call bullshit on that.

02:37.348 --> 02:38.718
The mayor wants us to think

02:38.751 --> 02:40.822
we're all living
on Main Street in Disneyland,

02:40.855 --> 02:44.529
but the truth is, Hackensack
is a haven for the bizarre,

02:44.563 --> 02:45.765
the fucked‐up,

02:45.798 --> 02:48.336
and the straight‐up
criminally insane.

02:48.370 --> 02:49.606
In the past year alone,

02:49.639 --> 02:52.378
our murder rate
has spiked 25%.

02:52.411 --> 02:54.315
In fact, we haven't seen
this kind of violence here

02:54.348 --> 02:56.520
since the Ray family murders
in '65,

02:56.553 --> 02:58.189
a bloodbath that gave birth

02:58.223 --> 03:01.195
to one of the most notorious
serial killers in history,

03:01.229 --> 03:03.466
Charles Lee Ray.

03:03.501 --> 03:05.772
Back in the day,
he was one of us,

03:05.805 --> 03:08.577
growing up right over
on Sherwood Lane.

03:08.611 --> 03:10.615
You won't read about it
in the "Times" dispatch,

03:10.648 --> 03:13.854
but you can hear all about it
right here, every week.

03:13.888 --> 03:16.392
Until next time,
fellow detectives,

03:16.426 --> 03:18.564
this is Devon Evans
bringing you...

03:18.597 --> 03:20.501
"Hackenslash."

03:23.473 --> 03:25.978
Binxie?
[clicking tongue]

03:26.012 --> 03:28.383
Here, Binx.

03:31.255 --> 03:34.228
[ambient music]

03:34.261 --> 03:41.375
♪ ♪

03:41.910 --> 03:44.248
[cat meows]

03:52.464 --> 03:53.868
How you doing, Binxie?

03:53.901 --> 03:55.270
[cat meows]

04:00.882 --> 04:02.619
[disturbing music]

04:02.652 --> 04:03.888
[cat meows]

04:03.921 --> 04:11.302
♪ ♪

04:13.874 --> 04:15.578
[cat hisses]

04:16.780 --> 04:20.855
♪ ♪

04:20.888 --> 04:24.361
[cat screeches, growls]

04:27.535 --> 04:29.840
Two heads are better than one,
right?

04:29.873 --> 04:34.649
♪ ♪

04:34.683 --> 04:36.587
[cat growls]

04:40.494 --> 04:43.601
[distant siren wailing]

04:55.925 --> 04:58.631
[cat growls]

05:05.812 --> 05:10.688
♪ ♪

05:10.721 --> 05:12.357
[cat meows]

05:18.002 --> 05:19.873
Let's see what you're really
made of.

05:19.906 --> 05:26.620
♪ ♪

05:26.653 --> 05:27.755
‐ Jake!

05:28.991 --> 05:31.095
Jake, I'm home.

05:34.034 --> 05:35.805
‐ Hey.
‐ [gasps]

05:35.838 --> 05:37.642
‐ Wanna play?

05:38.443 --> 05:40.882
‐ Jesus Christ, Jake,
another frickin' doll?

05:40.915 --> 05:42.752
‐ Hi, I'm Chucky,

05:42.785 --> 05:44.990
and I'm your friend
till the end.

05:45.023 --> 05:46.994
Hidey‐ho!
[laughs]

05:47.027 --> 05:48.764
‐ It's voice‐activated.

05:48.797 --> 05:52.004
Hey, I was thinking about using
his head for the sculpture.

05:52.037 --> 05:53.406
What do you think?

05:53.439 --> 05:56.647
‐ I don't know.
I'm no art critic.

05:56.680 --> 05:58.551
‐ Well, I'm not asking
for a review, Dad.

05:58.584 --> 06:02.592
I just want your opinion.
‐ It's cool, Jake.

06:02.625 --> 06:05.565
Still think you're spending
too much time on it.

06:05.598 --> 06:06.567
Wouldn't hurt you
to get out of this room

06:06.600 --> 06:08.136
every once in a while.

06:08.169 --> 06:10.975
Maybe you could, uh,
ask a girl to a movie.

06:11.008 --> 06:12.512
See a friend or something.

06:12.545 --> 06:15.383
‐ Friends come and go,
in my experience.

06:15.417 --> 06:16.485
The work lasts forever.

06:16.520 --> 06:18.891
‐ So does student debt.

06:18.924 --> 06:20.460
You know it's almost
impossible to make a living

06:20.493 --> 06:22.665
as an artist?

06:22.699 --> 06:25.403
‐ Mom did.
‐ That wasn't a living.

06:25.437 --> 06:26.607
That was a lifestyle,

06:26.640 --> 06:29.044
and it certainly
didn't pay the bills.

06:29.078 --> 06:30.948
I did.

06:30.982 --> 06:33.152
‐ [sighs]

06:36.893 --> 06:41.035
‐ You know you're looking more
and more like her every day?

06:41.068 --> 06:43.707
Speaking of which,
I looked into that art camp,

06:43.741 --> 06:46.546
and I don't think
it's gonna work out.

06:46.580 --> 06:50.053
‐ Why not?
‐ It's 1,000 bucks, Jake.

06:50.086 --> 06:53.861
I'm sorry.
Maybe next year.

06:53.894 --> 06:55.430
Besides,
you don't wanna be away from me

06:55.463 --> 06:57.200
for a whole month,
do you?

06:57.234 --> 06:59.071
[rock music
playing over stereo]

06:59.104 --> 07:00.808
You remember
to take your pill today?

07:00.841 --> 07:02.712
‐ Not yet.
‐ Well, you should take it.

07:02.745 --> 07:05.551
You're gonna need it.
We're at Defcon 1 tonight.

07:05.584 --> 07:07.454
‐ Why?
‐ Your cousin's coming over

07:07.487 --> 07:09.826
for dinner, remember?
‐ Oh, shit.

07:09.859 --> 07:12.497
‐ "Shit" is right.

07:12.532 --> 07:14.234
[cat growls]

07:14.268 --> 07:17.174
[suspenseful music]

07:17.207 --> 07:24.522
♪ ♪

07:30.133 --> 07:32.004
[cat hisses]

07:32.037 --> 07:35.010
[playful spooky music]

07:35.043 --> 07:41.923
♪ ♪

07:52.110 --> 07:54.683
‐ So this is fun.

07:54.716 --> 07:58.222
Can't remember last time
we just sent out for pizza.

07:58.256 --> 08:00.528
‐ Hey, Luke,

08:00.561 --> 08:03.232
you got a little something
on your, uh...

08:03.266 --> 08:06.807
Other side.
There you go.

08:06.840 --> 08:10.046
So how's business?
‐ It's not worth talking about.

08:10.080 --> 08:11.650
‐ Sure, it is.

08:11.683 --> 08:14.054
‐ Things could be better.

08:14.088 --> 08:16.092
I'm drowning.

08:16.125 --> 08:18.129
[menacing music]

08:18.162 --> 08:19.766
‐ Uh...

08:19.799 --> 08:22.237
I could throw you
a little business.

08:22.270 --> 08:24.074
Bree put a dent in her Lexus.

08:24.108 --> 08:25.276
‐ That'd be great...

08:25.310 --> 08:26.847
if we handled bodywork.

08:26.880 --> 08:30.120
♪ ♪

08:30.153 --> 08:31.757
But we don't.

08:31.790 --> 08:33.660
‐ There's no shame in getting
a little help now and then.

08:33.694 --> 08:36.165
‐ Who's ashamed?
‐ You're my brother.

08:36.198 --> 08:39.572
You'd do the same for me.

08:39.606 --> 08:42.310
‐ Come on, Logan.

08:42.344 --> 08:44.816
When have you ever needed help?

08:44.849 --> 08:51.763
♪ ♪

08:52.899 --> 08:54.903
‐ Well, Junior has some news.

08:54.936 --> 08:56.973
‐ Mom.
‐ Guess who made regionals.

08:57.007 --> 09:00.881
‐ Holy shit.
Oh, that's great, Junior.

09:00.915 --> 09:03.954
Isn't that great, Jake?
Huh?

09:03.987 --> 09:06.993
‐ He's the best distance runner
at Perry Middle since...

09:07.027 --> 09:08.831
well, since his father.
‐ [whispering] Yeah!

09:08.864 --> 09:12.104
‐ But regionals
is on the 10th.

09:12.137 --> 09:13.974
It's the day I'm painting
City Hall with the Scouts,

09:14.007 --> 09:15.110
remember?

09:15.143 --> 09:16.913
‐ You already made Eagle Scout,

09:16.947 --> 09:19.118
which reminds me,
you're gonna need

09:19.151 --> 09:21.055
another extracurricular.

09:21.088 --> 09:23.894
Harvard's gonna want three.

09:23.927 --> 09:26.700
If anyone can handle it,
you can.

09:28.236 --> 09:30.875
‐ You know, Jake, the, uh‐‐
the Scouts are taking gays now.

09:30.908 --> 09:32.344
You should totally come
check it out.

09:32.377 --> 09:35.718
‐ Junior.
‐ What? It's true.

09:35.751 --> 09:38.991
‐ So what does that mean,
exactly, Eagle Scout?

09:39.024 --> 09:41.195
Did you, like,
sell the most cookies?

09:41.228 --> 09:43.901
‐ No, while you were up in
your room playing with dolls,

09:43.934 --> 09:46.338
I organized a whole book drive
for the homeless.

09:46.372 --> 09:48.977
‐ Yeah, because keeping up
with Harry Potter

09:49.011 --> 09:51.917
is the most pressing issue
facing the homeless.

09:53.954 --> 09:55.825
‐ So, Jake, how is
the sculpture coming along?

09:55.858 --> 09:58.196
Can we see it yet?
‐ Soon.

09:58.229 --> 10:01.636
‐ Where do you get the dolls?
‐ Thrift shops, yard sales,

10:01.670 --> 10:03.707
eBay, trash cans.

10:03.740 --> 10:05.711
Andy Warhol once said,
"Just because something's

10:05.744 --> 10:07.682
been thrown away
doesn't make it garbage."

10:07.715 --> 10:09.251
‐ Wasn't Warhol gay too?

10:09.284 --> 10:11.088
‐ Junior, stop it.
‐ What?

10:11.122 --> 10:14.896
It's the 21st century.
It's cool to be gay now.

10:14.929 --> 10:16.933
Right, Jake?
‐ It's a nonissue.

10:16.967 --> 10:20.608
‐ Yeah, it's like
being left‐handed or vegan.

10:22.277 --> 10:25.116
‐ Would you give it a rest?

10:25.150 --> 10:27.655
He's 13 years old.
He doesn't know what he is.

10:27.688 --> 10:31.295
[menacing music]

10:31.328 --> 10:32.965
‐ 14.

10:36.740 --> 10:39.111
‐ Excuse me. Lucas,
where's your powder room?

10:39.144 --> 10:41.282
‐ It's upstairs
where it's always been.

10:41.315 --> 10:48.095
♪ ♪

10:55.811 --> 10:58.750
[eerie music]

10:58.784 --> 11:05.865
♪ ♪

11:11.175 --> 11:12.845
[cell phone beeps]

11:14.983 --> 11:18.322
‐ Hey, it's me.
[sighs]

11:18.356 --> 11:20.861
Sorry. I only have a minute.
I'm with my family.

11:20.895 --> 11:22.999
I just...
[rustling]

11:24.034 --> 11:26.740
[rustling]
I just needed‐‐

11:26.773 --> 11:30.013
[sighs]
Can you hold on a minute?

11:30.046 --> 11:37.027
♪ ♪

11:44.074 --> 11:46.478
[dramatic musical flourish]

11:46.513 --> 11:48.717
[sighs]

11:55.764 --> 11:58.469
[cat screeches]
Oh, my God!

11:58.503 --> 12:00.473
[cat growls]

12:00.507 --> 12:02.444
[sighs]

12:05.216 --> 12:08.757
Sorry, I thought someone
was in here with me.

12:08.790 --> 12:10.794
I really need to see you.

12:10.828 --> 12:12.798
Can I call you tomorrow?

12:14.134 --> 12:16.472
Okay.

12:16.506 --> 12:19.011
[engine turning over]

12:40.353 --> 12:42.090
‐ Binxie!

12:43.560 --> 12:45.831
Here, Binx.

12:49.973 --> 12:54.114
‐ [grunting, groaning]
[objects crashing]

12:54.147 --> 12:56.185
[menacing music]

12:56.218 --> 12:57.420
[grunting]

12:57.454 --> 13:04.769
♪ ♪

13:09.344 --> 13:11.448
[Madalen Duke's
"How Villains Are Made"]

13:11.482 --> 13:15.356
‐ ♪ Time to ♪

13:15.390 --> 13:19.164
♪ Put my medal on ♪

13:19.197 --> 13:21.135
♪ ♪

13:21.168 --> 13:22.571
♪ Whose blood to spill ♪

13:22.605 --> 13:24.842
♪ I don't know ♪

13:24.876 --> 13:26.579
‐ No more dolls, Jake.

13:26.613 --> 13:28.082
Ever.

13:28.115 --> 13:30.888
‐ ♪ Whose side I'm on ♪

13:30.921 --> 13:33.292
♪ ♪

13:33.326 --> 13:39.004
♪ Two armies
are coming at me ♪

13:39.037 --> 13:42.010
♪ Their flags and weapons
look the same ♪

13:42.043 --> 13:44.982
‐ [breathing shakily]

13:45.016 --> 13:49.291
‐ ♪ One tells the truth,
the other's lying ♪

13:49.324 --> 13:51.028
♪ ♪

13:51.061 --> 13:56.438
♪ And they're both
calling my name ♪

13:56.472 --> 14:02.250
♪ This is how villains
are made ♪

14:02.283 --> 14:08.162
♪ This is how
villains are made ♪

14:08.195 --> 14:12.270
♪ Oh, oh, oh, oh‐oh, oh, oh ♪

14:12.303 --> 14:14.207
♪ ♪

14:14.241 --> 14:19.519
♪ No one ever
starts that way ♪

14:19.552 --> 14:23.426
♪ But this is how villains
are made ♪

14:23.459 --> 14:28.603
♪ ♪

14:28.637 --> 14:30.339
‐ Binxie?

14:37.487 --> 14:40.594
[crows cawing] [suspenseful music]

14:40.627 --> 14:42.097
♪ ♪

14:42.130 --> 14:44.468
[keyboard clacking]

14:46.305 --> 14:48.977
[distant siren wailing]

14:49.010 --> 14:55.958
♪ ♪

14:57.393 --> 15:00.233
[keyboard clacking]

15:09.017 --> 15:12.123
‐ 1,500 bucks?

15:12.157 --> 15:13.459
Holy shit.

15:13.492 --> 15:16.398
[Kim Petras' "Personal Hell"]

15:16.432 --> 15:19.438
♪ ♪

15:19.471 --> 15:22.277
‐ ♪ Yeah, yeah ♪

15:22.310 --> 15:28.055
♪ ♪

15:28.088 --> 15:30.293
♪ Summer sun,
don't feel a thing ♪

15:30.326 --> 15:32.263
♪ Overthink 'bout everything ♪

15:32.297 --> 15:36.105
♪ When I think of you,
you give me chills ♪

15:36.138 --> 15:39.679
♪ Baby, come on,
got what I need ♪

15:39.712 --> 15:43.987
♪ Hands all over me, oh ♪

15:44.020 --> 15:46.526
♪ Save me ♪

15:46.559 --> 15:49.565
♪ From my personal hell ♪

15:49.599 --> 15:51.401
♪ Yeah, yeah ♪

15:51.435 --> 15:53.172
♪ Exorcise my demons, yeah ♪

15:53.205 --> 15:55.176
♪ Tainted love
could get me there ♪

15:55.209 --> 15:58.750
♪ I've been saving
all of this for you ♪

15:58.783 --> 16:03.125
♪ Baby, come on, over to me ♪

16:03.159 --> 16:06.431
♪ Come set me free ♪

16:06.465 --> 16:08.469
♪ Baby, come on ♪

16:08.503 --> 16:10.406
♪ Got what I need ♪

16:10.439 --> 16:14.181
♪ Hands all over me, oh ♪

16:14.214 --> 16:17.153
♪ Save me ♪

16:17.187 --> 16:18.557
♪ From my person‐‐ ♪

16:18.590 --> 16:20.493
[horn beeps]
‐ Hey, what up?

16:22.765 --> 16:24.334
‐ Still don't understand why
you're still into this stuff.

16:24.367 --> 16:25.604
It's so freaking weird.

16:25.637 --> 16:27.307
‐ I think it's a better hobby
than running.

16:27.340 --> 16:30.346
‐ ♪ Save me ♪

16:30.379 --> 16:33.285
♪ From my personal hell ♪

16:33.319 --> 16:34.755
♪ Yeah, yeah ♪

16:34.789 --> 16:38.563
♪ Break me,
break me out of myself ♪

16:38.597 --> 16:41.335
‐ Hey, Jake.
Awesome Good Guy.

16:41.368 --> 16:44.007
I'm into vintage too.
‐ Oh, he's retro.

16:44.040 --> 16:46.044
Wanna buy it?
‐ No, thanks.

16:46.078 --> 16:48.215
Hey, uh, can I ask you
a question?

16:48.249 --> 16:49.685
‐ Yeah, sure.

16:49.719 --> 16:52.758
‐ This is really awkward,
but do you think that you can,

16:52.791 --> 16:56.131
like, maybe introduce me
to your cousin?

16:56.164 --> 16:58.603
‐ [sighs] Junior?
‐ Yeah.

17:02.443 --> 17:03.780
‐ I get that a lot.

17:03.813 --> 17:07.721
I'm flattered, really,
but, um, it's not my thing.

17:09.559 --> 17:11.563
‐ Oh, sorry, I didn't know.

17:11.596 --> 17:15.069
‐ Yeah, since cotillion.
Don't you follow my Insta?

17:17.741 --> 17:20.714
‐ Your bed buddy, Jake?
What's his name?

17:20.747 --> 17:23.753
‐ What's your name?
‐ Hi, I'm Chucky.

17:23.787 --> 17:27.493
Wanna play?
‐ Oh, my God, that's adorable.

17:27.528 --> 17:30.534
Say, "Cheese."
‐ Chucky cheese.

17:30.567 --> 17:32.771
‐ You're not tearing him apart,
I hope.

17:32.805 --> 17:35.811
‐ Anything for art, right?
‐ No, you can't.

17:35.844 --> 17:37.681
‐ Well, actually,
I'm gonna sell him.

17:39.719 --> 17:43.359
‐ Oh, you're selling
your stuff now, Jake?

17:43.392 --> 17:46.298
I didn't realize
it'd gotten that bad.

17:46.331 --> 17:47.433
‐ No.
‐ I mean, do you need

17:47.467 --> 17:49.237
to borrow any money?
‐ No.

17:49.271 --> 17:51.475
‐ Seriously, it's no problem.

17:51.509 --> 17:52.778
Right?

17:52.811 --> 17:54.649
‐ You know I don't carry
cash on me.

17:54.682 --> 17:56.485
‐ You can Venmo.
‐ I'm fine.

17:56.519 --> 17:58.122
‐ Being financially
disadvantaged

17:58.155 --> 17:59.825
is nothing to be ashamed of,
Jake.

17:59.859 --> 18:01.295
Right?

18:01.328 --> 18:02.698
‐ I'm not.
[bell rings]

18:02.731 --> 18:06.204
‐ Well, see you later.
‐ Yeah, see you in class.

18:07.875 --> 18:11.616
‐ I just had
the most amazing idea.

18:11.649 --> 18:14.187
‐ Maybe you should
give the guy a break.

18:14.220 --> 18:15.524
‐ Don't go soft on me, babe.

18:15.557 --> 18:17.460
[bell rings]

18:17.493 --> 18:19.464
‐ E. B. White said
that explaining a joke

18:19.497 --> 18:22.303
is like dissecting a frog:

18:22.337 --> 18:24.675
you understand it better,

18:24.709 --> 18:29.819
but unfortunately,
the frog dies in the process.

18:32.625 --> 18:34.562
Jake, are you okay?

18:34.595 --> 18:36.566
‐ Uh, yeah, I just‐‐

18:36.599 --> 18:38.168
I don't‐‐
I don't think I can do this.

18:38.202 --> 18:40.874
